  <h2>How Pets Show Pain</h2>
  <p>
    Animals instinctively hide pain — a survival behavior that can make it easy to miss. Knowing what to look for is important for every pet owner. Common signs of pain or discomfort include:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Changes in behavior — becoming withdrawn, irritable, or unusually clingy</li>
    <li>Reduced activity or reluctance to climb stairs, jump, or play</li>
    <li>Changes in posture or gait — limping, hunching, or moving stiffly</li>
    <li>Decreased appetite or interest in food</li>
    <li>Excessive licking, biting, or scratching at a specific area</li>
    <li>Vocalizing — whimpering, growling, or crying when touched</li>
    <li>Changes in sleep patterns or difficulty settling</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If you notice any of these signs, don't wait. Chronic pain is progressive — the sooner it's addressed, the better the outcome.
  </p>

  <h2>Our Approach: Multimodal Pain Management</h2>
  <p>
    Effective pain management rarely relies on a single treatment. We use a multimodal approach — combining therapies to address pain from multiple angles, often achieving better results with lower doses of any single medication.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pharmaceutical management</strong> — NSAIDs, opioids, gabapentin, and other analgesics appropriate for your pet's condition and history</li>
    <li><strong>Laser therapy</strong> — low-level laser treatments that reduce inflammation and nerve sensitivity without medication</li>
    <li><strong>Joint supplements</strong> — omega-3 fatty acids, glucosamine, chondroitin, and other nutraceuticals with evidence-based benefit</li>
    <li><strong>Weight management</strong> — reducing mechanical load on painful joints through diet and appropriate exercise</li>
    <li><strong>Environmental modifications</strong> — ramps, orthopedic bedding, raised food bowls, and other practical adaptations</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Personalized Treatment Plans</h2>
  <p>
    Every pet's pain presentation is unique. A senior dog with hip dysplasia has different needs than a cat recovering from abdominal surgery. We build individualized plans that account for your pet's diagnosis, age, overall health, and how they respond to initial treatment — adjusting as needed.
  </p>
  <p>
    We also factor in your comfort level and practical constraints. A treatment plan that's difficult to maintain at home won't help your pet. We work with you to find approaches that are sustainable.
  </p>

